subject: BC REFUGEES DISASTER
title: 130 BOAT PEOPLE BELIEVED LOST IN TANKER COLLISION
author:  DAVID E. SANGER
text: 

       TOKYO -- Japanese officials disclosed Thursday that about 130
Vietnamese refugees are believed to have died earlier this month
when their overloaded boat apparently collided with a Japanese
tanker in the South China Sea.
       The accident occurred March 8, four days after the refugees left
Vietnam in a small fishing boat, the officials said. About 35 of
the refugees were rescued by the tanker, the 240,000-ton Nissei
Maru, as it was on the way to Malaysia.
       ``We have a sketchy outline of what happened,'' said Chikako
Saito, a spokeswoman for the Tokyo office of the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees. ``But there are conflicting
accounts of what happened.''
       Mrs. Saito said that survivors variously described the fishing
boat as being 27 feet or 51 feet long. When the boat left Vietnam,
they said, it was jammed with 165 people.
       Several of the survivors arrived in Yokohama, just south of
Tokyo, and were transferred to a holding center near Nagasaki in
southern Japan, the officials said.
       The Tokyo Shimbun newspaper reported Thursday that at around 11
a.m. on March 8 the fishing boat sighted the tanker and approached
it, but could not come alongside easily because of rough seas. On a
third attempt to approach the tanker, the fishing boat struck the
propeller of the tanker and immediately capsized.
       More than half of the fishing boat passengers died immediately,
the paper quoted one survivor as saying. ``I myself lost a
7-year-old daughter,'' the refugee was quoted as saying.
       NHK, the quasi-governmental Japanese network, said the tanker
stopped its engines as the boat approached. Officials from Tokyo
Tanker Co., which owns the craft, could not be reached for comment.
       The tanker's sailors threw life vests into the water and by 2
p.m. the fishing boat had reportedly sunk. The 35 survivors were
rescued late that afternoon.
       



