type: NYT (Copyright 1989 The New York Times)
priority: Regular
date: 03-23-89 0135EST
category: Domestic
subject: BC EAST STLOUIS
title: EAST ST. LOUIS FIGHTS FITFULLY TO SURVIVE
author:  ISABEL WILKERSON
text: 

       EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. -- Across the Mississippi River from the
bustle of St. Louis lies a city so indebted and lacking in basic
services that it evokes comparisons to the Third World.
       East St. Louis has not collected trash in a year. Mounds of
garbage lie uncollected in streets and vacant lots. Its decaying
sewer system has repeatedly backed up, heaving raw sewage onto the
streets and into houses and schools; the flooding and stench have
forced school buildings to close for days at a time.
       The city is $35 million in debt and is facing numerous lawsuits
for defaulting on its loans. It has stopped paying all but the most
crucial vendors, like those that provide gas for its police cars,
and it cannot afford even routine supplies, like soap and toilet
paper for City Hall.
       It is the subject of state and federal investigations into
allegations of mismanagement and reckless endangerment of its
citizens.
       The 308 municipal employees never know when they will be paid,
and must wait up to seven weeks for their paychecks. The city has
had to enlist state troopers to patrol its streets to fight its
worsening drug and gang problems.
       Last fall, as the sewer and debt crises deepened, Gov. James R.
Thompson set up a state group to investigate East St. Louis's
chronic problems.
       In December the panel declared that the city was in ``a state of
fiscal emergency'' and that its prospects for recovery appeared
``remote'' without state intervention.
       The group said East St. Louis needed a substantial loan to meet
its short-term obligations, but added that the state should not
make such a loan the city could identify a source of revenue to pay
it back.
       It recommended a complete fiscal reorganization and a
state-approved officer to sort through the city's jumbled finances.
       The state has set up an advisory board to approve the city's
financial actions. It is not clear where the process will lead.
       Although East St. Louis typifies the decline of many American
industrial cities, economists can think of few if any places where
the problems are so advanced, pervasive and extreme.
       ``It is a partially inhabited ghost town,'' said Charles Leven,
a professor of economics at Washington University in St. Louis.
``It is only in the most incidental sense a city. If it could have
annexed itself to another city, perhaps it would have been saved.''
       
       
        (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)

       
       
       East St. Louis was once a thriving river city, its economy built
on stockyards that fed the Middle West. By 1960, its population was
approaching 100,000. But advances in transportation and storage
caused the stockyards to shrink; many of them closed, and so did
other industries.
       The population fell rapidly. It is now just over 40,000, 60
percent of them on welfare. With the departure of so many
taxpayers, the city has become heavily dependent on state aid.
       To meet its payroll, investigators and some city officials say,
it routinely borrows against uncollected taxes and uses state aid
designated for functions like street repair.
       For the past 10 years, East St. Louis's mayor has been Carl E.
Officer, an aloof, self-confident, third-generation mortician, who
was re-elected two years ago in a race in which three of the 10
candidates were convicted felons.
       Officer, 36, a Democrat, acknowledges the city's financial
troubles but blames the loss of federal revenue sharing and the
hostility of the news media and of state and county officials, who,
he points out, are overwhelmingly white. Officer is black, as are
almost all East St. Louis residents.
       ``You always have people who say that the sky is falling and the
world is flat,'' said Officer. ``I live here; they don't. I'm at
peace with myself. Yes, we have vendors who are not paid on a
timely basis. We don't have a certain schedule. It's just the ebb
and flow of life.''
       Officer says he has a plan to save the city. It hinges on a $473
million riverfront industrial and residential project, to be
financed by industrial revenue bonds.
       The city has spent about $25 million on the project, but the
riverfront is still a bald wasteland, stalled by lawsuits and state
and federal investigations. Other problems aside, the land lies in
a flood plain, and critics of the Mayor doubt that it will ever be
built.
       Meanwhile, the city appears to be crumbling, vast stretches of
it looking as if they had been bombed. There are blocks and blocks
of burned houses, casualties of fires started by feuding drug
dealers or by kerosene heaters used to cut down on utility bills.
       City workers say the sporadic paychecks and low morale have
crippled city services. For months, the city has ignored the
demands from its creditors.
       The city's largest employer, the public school system, is facing
a $12 million deficit and plans to lay off a third of its 1,000
classroom teachers April 1.
       ``People hoped the problem would go away,'' said Elmo Bush,
superintendent of schools. ``But it can't be denied any longer.''
       Leven said he did not foresee a turnaround any time soon. ``I
don't think there is any way you can make much out of what is there
now,'' he said. ``The best you can do is keep the patient
comfortable.''
       



