          Thank you all for your concerned responses to my observation
on a cultural difference between Japan and the US. I must after
this remain silent because I have two little ones at home (one still in
diapers), a marriage that takes time, and a dissertation to finish.
I would enjoy moving over to info-japan and discussing
many things about my visit to Japan with you.   I have "lots" more
to say about women, for example.  And I suspect you all do too.
And then there are the hot springs, earthquake experiences, eating
attitudes, consumer attitudes, work ethics, etc.

          Please do not be disturbed by my raving.  Long ago when
moving from red neck America, to intellectual white collar America,
I learned to cope with the very things I touched on in my past message.
The Japanese gentleman's entry into my life has only made "things" more
interesting, ... the way I like it.   We all marry into strange tribes.
The differences are just a "tad" more pronounced between mine and my
husband's. 

           You heard from me at a time in which the family is going
through many changes.  The parallel is learning a new technique
in tennis (or strategy in chess).  At first, it seems like you are
losing ground and your performance seems horrible.  But
in the end you become stronger and improved ... able to play the
game better.  I suspect this applies to learning Japanese too.

To those concerned about my son's wrists, thank you for your suggestions.
I am just learning to be an avocate of his learning style within the system
(WOW, there are so many systems!) 
"Slapping wrists" meant verbal negative reenforcement in the U.S.,
and a slap on the thigh in Japan.  In trying to be brief, my
language became sloppy. Sorry.  

We'll try to hang in there with the
Japanese language. We believe that education is the best
gift that parents give to their youngsters, whether
it be sewing, swimming, a foreign language or loving....  What ever
you do well, don't be stingy, pass it on if you can...

        So now I retire to listen to your mail about the Japanese
language.  The thing that most disturbs ME about my last letter
is my admission that my Japanese is still so horrible even though
there are many reasons I should learn it well.  Maybe after
the baby is out of diapers and the dissertation is done ....?

